## First — Virtual Threads Don't Make Code Async!

This is a **critical misconception.**

```java
// This is still SYNCHRONOUS code
Thread.ofVirtual().start(() -> {
    String result = callAPI(); // waiter STILL waits for food
    updateDb(result);          // then does next step
});
```

The **code flow** is synchronous — top to bottom.
What changes is what happens to the **carrier thread** during the wait.

---

## The Real Picture

```
SYNCHRONOUS (Platform Thread):
──────────────────────────────
Carrier/OS Thread:
[doing work]──[BLOCKED waiting]──[doing work]
                    ↑
              OS thread wasted
              CPU core idle


SYNCHRONOUS (Virtual Thread):
──────────────────────────────
Virtual Thread:  [doing work]──[BLOCKED waiting]──[doing work]
                                      ↑
                               VT unmounted here

Carrier Thread:  [doing work]──[picks up VT-B]──[picks up VT-C]──[resumes VT-A]
                                      ↑
                          Carrier NEVER idle!
```

---

## How Many Virtual Threads Per Carrier Thread?

**No fixed limit — it's dynamic and depends on blocking behavior.**

```
Carrier Threads = Number of CPU cores (say 8 cores = 8 carriers)

Scenario: Each virtual thread blocks for 1 second

t=0ms   Carrier-1 picks VT-1  → blocks → picks VT-2  → blocks → picks VT-3...
        In 1ms it can mount/unmount hundreds of virtual threads!

Theoretically:
  1 carrier thread, tasks blocking 1 second each
  Carrier spends ~0.1ms mounting/unmounting
  In 1 second → 1000ms / 0.1ms = can cycle through ~10,000 VTs!
```

```
Real world numbers:
─────────────────────────────────────
Carrier threads    : 8  (CPU cores)
Virtual threads    : 1,000,000
Ratio              : 125,000 VTs per carrier thread
```

